{"source_key":"sha256-c6b76f7f2235b4e1596b54cc99ecb555","record_index":620,"record_hash":"sha256:ef0ccceac5734883b2d8b2f87efb5baa9b88ea47c0961ec5d05c2387fc143bb2","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:19:03.905Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"No serious API/RAII bug found. The lock shape is basically sound, and `cargo test -p but-agentlog -- --nocapture` passes: 32 tests green.\\n\\n**Findings**\\n\\n- [environment.rs:610](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:610): `ReadOnlyRefMetadata` mutators silently return success. Bad footgun: if `but_workspace::head_info` or future code ever mutates through `RefMetadata`, agentlog will pretend it persisted. Make it fail loud.\\n\\n```diff\\n fn set_workspace(&mut self, _value: &Self::Handle<Workspace>) -> anyhow::Result<()> {\\n-    Ok(())\\n+    anyhow::bail!(\\\"agentlog read-only metadata cannot be mutated\\\")\\n }\\n\\n fn set_branch(&mut self, _value: &Self::Handle<Branch>) -> anyhow::Result<()> {\\n-    Ok(())\\n+    anyhow::bail!(\\\"agentlog read-only metadata cannot be mutated\\\")\\n }\\n\\n fn remove(&mut self, _ref_name: &gix::refs::FullNameRef) -> anyhow::Result<bool> {\\n-    Ok(false)\\n+    anyhow::bail!(\\\"agentlog read-only metadata cannot be mutated\\\")\\n }\\n```\\n\\n- [gitmeta.rs:670](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:670): `concurrent_capture_serializes_dedupe` is useful, but it doesnãt directly prove `with_capture_lock()` blocks a second entrant while the first holds the lock. Add a small `capture_lock.rs` unit test with channels: first thread enters lock and waits; second thread should not enter before release. That tests the lock, not just final GitMeta dedupe.\\n\\n- [capture_lock.rs:16](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/capture_lock.rs:16): `CaptureLock` is a wrapper around `LockFile` with a `Drop` that only calls `unlock()` and ignores the result. Since `fslock::LockFile` already unlocks on drop under `but_core::sync::LockFile`, this wrapper is ceremony. Prefer returning `LockFile` from an `acquire_capture_lock()` helper and let RAII do the work.\\n\\n```diff\\n-struct CaptureLock { file_lock: LockFile }\\n+fn acquire_capture_lock(repo_path: &Path) -> Result<LockFile> {\\n+    ...\\n+    Ok(file_lock)\\n+}\\n```\\n\\n- [environment.rs:53](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:53): visibility is wider than needed for `PathList`, `StackSnapshot`, `BranchSnapshot`, and likely `SnapshotErrorKind`. Their fields are private and theyãre only serialized through `EnvironmentSnapshot`; keep only `SnapshotStatus`, `EnvironmentSnapshot`, `ObservedTargets`, and `EnvironmentObservation` crate-visible.\\n\\nThe dependency choices are defensible: `but-core`/`but-workspace` for repo/workspace semantics, `but-meta` legacy only to read old virtual branch metadata, `bstr` for Git paths, `toml` for metadata parsing. No dependency smells beyond the legacy import being worth a comment near `ReadOnlyRefMetadata`.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:19:03.905Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}